2025-12-12 | Detect Redundant Parentheses in an Expression

	Question
Given a balanced expression string s,  
check if it contains any redundant parentheses.  
Return true if redundant parentheses exist, otherwise false.

	Approach
1.	Use a **stack-based approach**.
2.	Traverse the string character by character.
3.	Push every character onto the stack **except closing ')'**.
4.	When a closing parenthesis ')' is encountered:
	-	Pop elements from the stack until '(' is found.
	-	Check whether there was **at least one operator** inside the parentheses.
5.	If no operator is found before encountering '(':
	-	The parentheses are redundant â†’ return true.
6.	Pop the '(' from the stack and continue.
7.	If the entire string is processed without detecting redundancy:
	-	Return false.
8.	Time Complexity: O(n)  
   Space Complexity: O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    bool redundantParentheses(string s) {
        stack<char> st;

        for (char ch : s) {
            if (ch == ')') {
                bool hasOperator = false;

                while (!st.empty() && st.top() != '(') {
                    char top = st.top();
                    st.pop();

                    if (top == '+' || top == '-' ||
                        top == '*' || top == '/')
                        hasOperator = true;
                }

                // Pop the opening '('
                if (!st.empty())
                    st.pop();

                // If no operator was found, parentheses are redundant
                if (!hasOperator)
                    return true;
            } else {
                st.push(ch);
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
